03694nmm a2200661Ia 9780520913653DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20231994cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209136537 a10.1525/97805209136532doi  a(DE-B1597)569664  a(OCoLC)1198931943  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBV3427.E8bA3 1994 7aREL0700002bisacsh04a951.04/1/092aB2201 aEspey, John H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMinor Heresies, Major Departures :bA China Mission Boyhood /cJohn H. Espey.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (357 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn American boy, son of Presbyterian missionaries, was born in Shanghai early in this century. The boy lived two lives, one within the pious church compound, the other along the canal and in the alleys of a traditional Chinese city. There he faced the alley brats' Lady Bandit, heard the shrill screams of a child's foot-binding, learned rank obscenities from passing boatmen, and, while still in short pants, chewed Sen-Sen and ogled snake-charmers in the old Native City. He sailed up the Yangtze to attend boarding school, and along with his Boy Scout patrol, met Chiang Kai-shek. And when John Espey grew up, he wrote about his years in China.This memoir is the story of those years, and while it is a wry, affectionate account, it also conveys an often overlooked picture of China in the years before communism. Seen through the eyes of a child, the interplay of religion, commerce, and American colonialism that took place during this period is revealed more tellingly—and more lightheartedly—than in many an analysis by an "old China hand."Espey's bent is to use a "Chinese" approach to his subject, that is, to hide a second meaning within his words, to speak in parables. This he learned from both his single-minded missionary father and the family's Chinese cook. The result is that the reader of Minor Heresies, Major Departures will learn a great deal about the Pacific Rim while having a rollicking good time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aMissions, AmericanxChinaxShanghai. 0aMissions, AmericanzChinazShanghai. 4aAmerica. 4aAmerican literature. 4aAsian history. 4aChina. 4aChristianity. 4aEnglish Literature. 4abiography. 4ahistory. 4aindividual authors. 4aliterature. 4amission studies. 4apoetry. 4apoets. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520913653?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520913653423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520913653/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles